good afternoon and welcome everyone i am felix overall Tucci I serve as chair of
the MBA program and I'm delighted to welcome all of you families friends
faculty colleagues and staff and of
course the incomparable class of 2017 to
our graduation ceremony I am actually not quite sure who ordered the rain but
we can always use an extra fuse to cuddle up there are many reasons why
this day is special you worked hard for it
battled through hundreds of cases and a seemingly never-ending string of
late-night strangely themed parties but
they say it's extra special because we get to celebrate it with family and friends none of us would be here without
their support their encouragement and good advice confidence that we all can
be successful today we celebrate you our graduates and in doing so we celebrate
them we will now hear from our Dean
professor Nitin Nohria [Applause]
for six years we somehow managed to get great weather and I thought we would be seventh year lucky especially since I
had a daughter graduating from the other side today too but it wasn't to be in any case class of 2017 friends and
family and members of the Harvard Business School community good afternoon and welcome your class the class of 2017
has witness during its time here at Harvard Business School a series of
remarkable global political events Great Britain surprise decision to lead the
European Union one of the most contentious American elections in our nation's history and just recently the closely watched
presidential race in France today as you prepare to leave our campus and start
the next chapter of you of your lives in what can only be described as an increasingly divided and fast shifting
world I want to offer some parting thoughts specific to the Tillich challenging times in which we find
ourselves because I'm fond of alliteration I'm going to talk to you
about three hours they are responsibilities reach and respect your responsibilities as people
trained to lead business are more important today than ever before you are
graduating into a world in which trust and faith in business has declined significantly in the u.s. unemployment
may be at record lows and the stock market at record highs but these data points do not offer comfort to those who
experience firsthand the wide and growing inequality in how the value
created by businesses is shared with society simply put many view the
capitalist system in deep need of repair as leaders part of your responsibility
is to rebuild this trust between business and society
my hope is that the many discussions you have had in courses as varied as
leadership and corporate accountability and Finance have given you tools and
perspectives that will serve as a guide to you in the future I hope you have
developed and that you will continue to develop both the competence and
character of true leadership you will need both to fulfill your responsibility
to rebuild trust the way that you can do so is by creating shared prosperity in
essence by ensuring that you create value for others before you claim value
for yourself you can fulfill your responsibility by behaving ethically and
by showing concern for interests other than your own you can fulfill it by
living by a managerial version of the Hippocratic oath taken by students
graduating across the river today at the Harvard Medical School simply put it
starts with a very powerful principle at a minimum do no harm
you can exercise your responsibility to help rebuild trust not only by the big
decisions you make leading organizations but also by the smaller interactions you
have every day leaders rightly are scrutinized more carefully than others
so even small signs of arrogance excessive pride or self-interest will
inevitably be magnified hold yourself to a higher standard imagine that some day
you may be the case protagonist that future generations of MBAs will learn
about ask yourself how can I be a leader students will want to emulate remember
you are a true leader only when you have earned the respect and trust of others
when others recognize you as such I want
you to think about how you will respond when you face the inevitable criticism that leadership attracts no one likes
this part of the job it's a natural instinct to react defensively to
discount or to fight back in our classrooms though we teach that learning
from feedback including negative feedback is an essential act of effective leadership all of you
experience moments when classmates disagreed with your views indeed one of
the many benefits of the case method is that one learns to handle such everyday
conflict with grace as you think about the responsibilities you take on as you
graduate today keep in mind that despite the criticisms that may be levied at
businesses and their leaders when business enterprises are led responsibly
they can be a powerful force for good this is something I personally came to
appreciate deeply during my childhood my father grew up in India in a village
with no electricity he learned to read by candlelight in a home that routinely
reached 110 degrees in the summer because there was no air conditioning or even fans as an adult my father rose to
become CEO of a company that works to bring electricity to every part of India
he always had a deep appreciation for how the product he was selling would
change the lives of his customers and how the jobs his company was creating
could transform the lives of his employees I witnessed this growing up and it gave me a palpable sense that
businesses have a unique capacity to make the world a better place it's why I
chose to devote my career to educating people to become responsible business
leaders as a professor and now Dean of this institution this sensibility has
grown as I have witnessed the lives led by our graduates some of whom you met
yesterday many of our alumni currently lead some of the most admired and valuable companies on the planet
they have been crucial to the creation and evolution of entire industries
including management consulting neutral funds private equity venture capital and
social entrepreneurship to name just a few they are striving to transform economies whether on a local national or
global scale and in doing so are working to lift literally hundreds of millions
of people out of poverty if you want your lives to have that kind of impact
you must reach I use that word to refer to how you should stretch for things
that seem just a little outside your grasp just a bit audacious when we reach
we take a risk that has the potential to fundamentally shift the trajectory of
our lives and our organizations and of other people when you think about reach
ask also how you might reach to try and solve some of the biggest problems we
are facing in society today issues like inequality seem so daunting that can be
tempting to sit back and wait for government and policy leaders who will legislate or regulate solutions I'd urge
you to resist this temptation and instead to reach to be part of the
solution some businesses have already begun to lead the way on such issues
including living wages equal rights and sustainability many of the leaders of
these businesses have said that they have been inspired by the ideals of young leaders just like you to take on
these horses the time is ripe for you to make a difference it's up to you to help
steer the businesses you will join to reach for solutions to society's most
challenging issues often our biggest sense of accomplishment comes not when
we reach for ourselves but when we reach out on behalf of others experiences most
often when I deal with our alumni who give back to so many causes today you
join a group of a nine who are distinguished not only as leaders but as philanthropists and
energetic civic participants people who lead and fund countless nonprofits and
philanthropies it is a privilege for me to spend time with these people because I witnessed
firsthand the palpable joy they feel when they can experience the impact they
have on others so as all of you think about making audacious reaches over the
course of your life I would urge you not just to consider what you can reach for
yourselves but how you might reach out generously on behalf of others as well
finally I ask you to consider a third vital behavior that of respect show
respect on a daily basis to everyone you interact with your co-workers and
customers your global partners and your local communities your supporters and
your detractors and especially to those less powerful whose work can sometimes
go unnoticed as leaders you will often get more credit than you deserve be sure
to share this credit by giving respect to all who contribute to any success let
me in that same spirit take a moment to thank every member of our horrible
school community faculty and staff both those who work front stage and those who
work backstage who have collectively helped to educate you and bring you to
this wonderful moment of graduation please join me inside
in this vein of respect as you commence life ahead one of the specific
challenges you will face is balancing the demands of your career with the rest of your life in this arena in particular
I'd urge all of you to respect your loved ones as the number one priority in
your lives Tom DeLonge one of our senior faculty uses a metaphor from the world
of auto racing to describe a trap we risk falling into in auto racing the
goal is to run as many laps as quickly as you can then when it's time to refuel
and put new tires on the racecar the driver pulls off the track to make a pit
stop in racing one of the keys to victory is making quick pit stops in
other words the goal of racing is to spend as little time off the track as
possible as you begin careers that will be challenging and even enthralling some
of you may fall into the trap of treating your work lives like the
racetrack and your home like the pit stop if you remember nothing else I say
to you today please remember this resist that fraud no matter how successful you
are in your career you will never be happy unless you are respecting your loved ones with the gift of your time
your presence and your full attention even if it requires you to step away
from work at times that are inconvenient as each of you think about the best ways
to respect the people who are important in your lives I'm sure your thoughts will immediately turn to the family and
guess who are celebrating with you as you graduate today so members of the class of 2017 let's take a moment to
show this respect please stand up turn around
as much as today is a celebration of you and what you have accomplished none of it would be possible without the
strong support you receive from others the husbands wives partners parents
sisters brothers on uncles cousins and friends who've nurtured you and
encouraged you maybe it was one special individual behind you or a team maybe it
was simply someone who believed in you early on so join me once again in recognizing them and showing them your
respect ok turn back around the faculty
and I joined your families friends and well-wishers in congratulating you on
all you have accomplished during your time with us we celebrate you and we
wish you good luck as you begin your next adventures we encourage you to be
mindful of your responsibilities as leaders at a time when business must
work to rebuild the public's trust we remind you to reach to word ambitious
goals that will help Society of society's most pressing problems and we
ask that you respect the people who are most important in your lives and everyone with whom you interact along
your road to leadership remember nothing can be accomplished without the help of
others as you begin this exciting new chapter in your lives I wish you all the
